{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=National Railroad Passenger Corporation v. Boston & Maine Corp. |ArgueDate=January 13 |ArgueYear=1992 |DecideDate=March 25 |DecideYear=1992 |FullName=National Railroad Passenger Corporation v. Boston & Maine Corp. |USVol=503 |USPage=407 |ParallelCitations=112 S. Ct. 1394; 118 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 52; 1992 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 1952 |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding=Amtrak may condemn a railroad's trackage and convey it to another railroad to continue intercity passenger service; the [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] reasonably interpreted {{UnitedStatesCodeSub|45|562|d}}. |SCOTUS=1991-1993 |Majority=Kennedy |JoinMajority=Rehnquist, Stevens, O'Connor, Scalia, Souter |Concurrence= |JoinConcurrence= |Concurrence2= |JoinConcurrence2= |Concurrence/Dissent= |JoinConcurrence/Dissent= |Dissent=White |JoinDissent=Blackmun, Thomas |Dissent2= |JoinDissent2= |LawsApplied={{UnitedStatesCodeSub|45|562|d}} }} '''''National Railroad Passenger Corporation v. Boston & Maine Corp.''''', 503 U.S. 407 (1992), was a case in which the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] ruled that the National Railroad Passenger Corporation (better known as [[Amtrak]]), could condemn railroad property from [[Boston and Maine Corporation|Boston and Maine Railroad]] and convey it to another railroad in order to continue [[passenger rail]] service over that route.
==History== {{main|Montrealer (train)}} The ''[[Montrealer (train)|Montrealer]]'' was originally a service of the [[Boston and Maine Railroad]] which used B&M's [[Connecticut River Line]] south of [[Vernon, Vermont]] to reach [[New York City]]. The NYC-Montréal portion of this route was continued under [[Amtrak]].
The ''Montrealer'' was suspended from early April 1987 to mid-July 1989 because of deteriorating track conditions on the Boston and Maine Railroad, which had been taken over by [[Guilford Transportation]]. During the suspension, Amtrak offered "Ambus" service (operated by Vermont Transit).
To restore passenger rail service, Amtrak seized the section of the line between [[Windsor, Vermont|Windsor]] and [[Brattleboro, Vermont|Brattleboro]] by [[eminent domain]]. The track was rebuilt using federal funds and sold to the [[Central Vermont Railway]]. The train was reinstated in July 1989, continuing until 1995 on a modified route which used the Central Vermont Railway (now the [[New England Central Railroad]]) from East Northfield to [[New London, Connecticut]].
The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] upheld Amtrak's action.<ref name="solomon" />{{rp|47}}
